    date: "2026-06-24",
    title: "Is cancer secretly a metabolic disease?",
    excerpt: "The Warburg effect is getting a second look — and it's changing how some cancers are treated.",
    table: "<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><caption>Two ways of explaining cancer, side by side</caption><tr><th>Question</th><th>Genetic theory (mainstream)</th><th>Metabolic theory (challenger)</th></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">Primary cause</td><td>Accumulated DNA mutations</td><td>Damaged mitochondrial energy production</td></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">Warburg effect</td><td>A downstream side effect</td><td>A central driver of malignancy</td></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">Key evidence</td><td>Oncogenes, Cancer Genome Atlas</td><td>Near-universal metabolic rewiring across tumor types</td></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">Leading voice</td><td>Robert Weinberg (MIT)</td><td>Thomas Seyfried (Boston College)</td></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">Treatment implication</td><td>Targeted gene/pathway drugs</td><td>Ketogenic diets, fasting, metabolic drugs (adjunct)</td></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">Current consensus</td><td colspan=\"2\">Likely both: mutations initiate, metabolic rewiring drives aggressiveness — not an either/or</td></tr></table></div>",
    sources: [
      { label: "Cancer as a Metabolic Disease — Thomas Seyfried (Wiley, 2012)", url: "https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/book/10.1002/9781118310311" },
      { label: "Book review of Cancer as a Metabolic Disease (PMC)", url: "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4102745/" },
      { label: "Thomas Seyfried's research page (Boston College)", url: "https://tomseyfried.com/" }
    ],
    body: "For most of the last century, cancer has been understood almost entirely as a genetic disease — a cell accumulates mutations, escapes its normal controls, and multiplies. That's still the dominant model. But a rival idea, dormant since the 1920s, has been quietly gaining ground: that cancer is at least partly a metabolic disease, rooted in how cells produce energy rather than only in their DNA.\n\nThe idea traces back to Otto Warburg, who noticed in the 1920s that cancer cells ferment glucose into lactate even when oxygen is plentiful — a wasteful, oxygen-ignoring way to make energy that healthy cells only use under stress. For decades this was treated as a side effect of cancer, not a cause. Modern metabolomics has revived the question: this metabolic rewiring shows up in nearly every cancer studied, which is hard to write off as incidental.\n\nThe case for taking it seriously has built from several directions at once. Genetic-only treatments keep running into the same wall — a targeted drug works, then the tumour finds a workaround, often by switching fuel sources rather than acquiring a new mutation. Epidemiology adds another thread: obesity, diabetes, and metabolic syndrome all raise cancer risk and aggressiveness, which is odd if cancer is purely a genetic accident unrelated to metabolism. And funding has followed the evidence — cancer metabolism research, PET scans that quite literally visualise the Warburg effect, and drugs aimed at metabolic pathways are now mainstream, not fringe.\n\nThe most vocal advocate for a metabolism-first view is Thomas Seyfried at Boston College, who argues mitochondrial dysfunction is the primary driver and genetic instability is downstream of it, laid out in his book Cancer as a Metabolic Disease. He's not alone: researchers at USC, MIT, and the University of South Florida are all investigating angles from fasting-mimicking diets to ketogenic protocols to hyperbaric oxygen, largely as adjuncts to standard treatment rather than replacements for it. On the other side, geneticists like Robert Weinberg at MIT remain unconvinced that metabolism is the primary driver, even as their own research on the tumour microenvironment keeps bumping into metabolic questions.\n\nWhere this seems to be landing is not a replacement of one theory by the other, but a synthesis: genetic mutations likely still initiate most cancers, but the metabolic rewiring that follows is what allows a tumour to grow aggressively, evade the immune system, and resist treatment — and that rewiring can itself cause further mutations, creating a loop between the two mechanisms rather than a competition between them.\n\nNone of this has produced a metabolic cure. Ketogenic and fasting-based approaches remain investigational, showing the most promise so far in specific cancers like glioblastoma, and are not a substitute for standard oncology. But the fact that a 100-year-old, largely dismissed observation is now shaping drug development and clinical trials is itself notable — a reminder that today's fringe theory is sometimes tomorrow's second pillar.",
    summary: "Cancer has long been treated as purely a genetic disease, but an older idea — that it's also a disease of cellular energy production — is regaining credibility. Otto Warburg noticed in the 1920s that cancer cells make energy inefficiently even with oxygen available; for decades that was dismissed as a side effect. Now: genetic-only drugs keep hitting resistance as tumours switch fuel sources rather than just mutating further, obesity and diabetes are strongly linked to cancer risk, and funding for cancer-metabolism research has surged, including PET scans that visualise this effect directly. Thomas Seyfried is the leading advocate for metabolism as the primary driver; most researchers now favour a synthesis instead — genetic mutations start the process, metabolic rewiring is what lets the cancer grow aggressively and resist treatment, and the two reinforce each other. Diet-based approaches like ketogenic or fasting protocols are being tested as add-ons to standard treatment, mainly in cancers like glioblastoma, not as replacements for it.",
    simple: "Scientists used to think cancer was almost entirely caused by damaged genes. There's a growing idea that it's also about how cancer cells make energy — they use a strange, inefficient method even when there's plenty of oxygen around, something first spotted 100 years ago and mostly ignored since. Now doctors are paying more attention because treatments that only target genes often stop working as tumours find new ways to fuel themselves, and conditions like obesity and diabetes make cancer more likely and more aggressive, which fits an energy-based explanation. The current thinking is that both ideas are true together: damaged genes usually start a cancer, but the energy changes are what let it grow strong and dodge treatment. Some cancer centers are now testing diets like fasting or keto alongside normal treatment — not instead of it."
