    date: "2026-06-19",
    title: "The healthy living handbook",
    excerpt: "Food, exercise, sleep, stress, and fasting — the whole evidence-based picture in one place.",
    table: "<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><caption>Quick daily reference</caption><tr><th>Time of day</th><th>What to do</th></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">Morning</td><td>10–15 min outdoor light, water before coffee, a slow protein+fat+fibre breakfast, box breathing if stressed</td></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">During the day</td><td>Move every 30–60 min, whole food over packaged snacks, water over juice</td></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">After meals</td><td>A 10-min walk when possible, especially after dinner — blunts the blood sugar spike</td></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">Exercise</td><td>~30 min Zone 2 cardio most days, resistance training 2–3x/week, wall sits during TV time</td></tr><tr><td class=\"hl\">Evening</td><td>Dim lights by 9pm, no screens 30–60 min before bed, cool room, consistent sleep time</td></tr></table></div>",
    body: "Most health advice fails not because the science is wrong but because it asks for too much change at once. This is an attempt to lay out the evidence-based basics for cardiovascular and metabolic health — food, movement, sleep, stress, and fasting — in one place, without pretending any of it requires perfection.\n\nOn food, the goal is a consistent pattern rather than a perfect diet. The foods worth eating more of: extra virgin olive oil as your primary fat (the PREDIMED trial found roughly a 30% reduction in cardiovascular events with heavy olive oil use), fatty fish two to three times a week for omega-3s, leafy greens daily for potassium and nitrates, berries for their anti-inflammatory anthocyanins, avocado and walnuts for monounsaturated fats, legumes several times a week, and garlic, onions, and cruciferous vegetables for their blood-pressure and anti-inflammatory effects. On the other side: sugar and refined carbohydrates are the main driver of high triglycerides and insulin resistance; most dietary sodium comes from processed food rather than the salt shaker; alcohol reliably raises blood pressure and triglycerides even in moderate amounts; seed oils oxidise badly at high heat; and ultra-processed food drives inflammation independent of its individual ingredients. For blood pressure specifically, potassium (3500–4700mg/day), magnesium (400–500mg/day), beet juice or other dietary nitrates, and the DASH eating pattern all have solid trial evidence behind them, with DASH alone showing 8–14 mmHg systolic reductions.\n\nOn movement, aerobic and resistance training combined outperform either alone. Zone 2 cardio — steady effort where you can still hold a conversation — for 150–200 minutes a week builds the aerobic base. Resistance training two to three times weekly is, somewhat surprisingly, one of the more powerful tools for metabolic health, since muscle is the body's primary glucose disposal site. Isometric holds — wall sits, planks, handgrip squeezes — have shown blood pressure reductions in recent trials that sometimes exceed aerobic exercise, and a ten-minute walk after a meal measurably blunts the blood sugar spike that follows eating.\n\nSleep is not passive downtime — it's when hormone regulation, insulin sensitivity, and cardiovascular repair happen. Seven to nine hours is the target, consistent timing matters as much as total hours, a cool dark room (17–19°C) supports the temperature drop needed for deep sleep, and morning light within an hour of waking sets the circadian clock that governs the rest of the cycle. Alcohol near bedtime reliably fragments sleep architecture even when it helps you fall asleep faster.\n\nChronic stress keeps the sympathetic nervous system engaged, which raises blood pressure, blood sugar, and inflammation on an ongoing basis — which makes stress management a legitimate piece of cardiovascular medicine, not just a wellness add-on. Slow breathing (four to six breaths a minute), regular time outdoors, limiting news consumption, and strong social connection all have measurable effects on stress hormones.\n\nIntermittent fasting — eating within a set daily window, most commonly 16:8 — has reasonable trial evidence for lowering fasting insulin, improving triglycerides and HDL, and improving insulin sensitivity independent of weight loss. The practical advice is to start with a twelve-hour window and extend gradually, to be careful with electrolytes and blood pressure medication timing if those apply, and to break a fast with protein, fat, and vegetables rather than refined carbohydrates.\n\nNone of this requires doing everything simultaneously. Small, consistent changes compound — the goal is a sustainable pattern, not a perfect week.",
    summary: "A condensed, evidence-based reference covering five areas of cardiovascular and metabolic health. Food: prioritise olive oil, fatty fish, leafy greens, berries, legumes; minimise sugar, refined carbs, processed sodium, alcohol, and seed oils; potassium, magnesium, and the DASH diet all have solid blood-pressure evidence. Exercise: combine aerobic (Zone 2, 150–200 min/week) with resistance training (2–3x/week) and consider isometric holds and post-meal walks, both surprisingly effective for blood pressure and blood sugar. Sleep: 7–9 hours, consistent timing, a cool dark room, and morning light matter more than any single supplement. Stress: chronic stress directly raises blood pressure and blood sugar, so breathing exercises, time outdoors, and social connection count as cardiovascular tools. Fasting: time-restricted eating (commonly 16:8) has good evidence for insulin and triglycerides, started gradually and broken with a real meal rather than refined carbs. The overall message: small consistent habits beat any single perfect intervention."
